'''Laconism''' is a figure of speech in which someone uses very few words to express an idea. This may be used for efficiency (like in military jargon), for philosophical reasons (especially among thinkers who believe in minimalism, such as [[Stoicism|stoicians]]), for better disarming a long, pompous speech (the most famous example being at the [[Battle of Thermopylae]]) or, simply, a consequence of poor litterary education (arguably, this is the real reason why [[Sparta|Spartans]] were concise at Thermopylae; the rhetorical consequence of their laconism is just an unvoluntary, positive and surprising consequence).

''Laconism'' comes from [[Laconia]] (a.k.a. ''[[Lacedaemon]]'' [greek ''Λακεδαίμων'']), the region surrounding the city of Sparta ''stricto censu'', region which was under the control of the city.

==Famous example==
(Thermopylae)
*Persian emissary: [long speech, ending with “our arrows will blot out the sun”]
*Leonidas: “Good. Then we will fight in the shade”

